# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hbm-memory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hbm-memory/gddr-sdram] GDDR was initially known as DDR SGRAM (double data rate synchronous graphics RAM).
[src:hbm-memory/gddr-sdram] It was commercially introduced as a 16 Mb memory chip by Samsung Electronics in 1998.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr-sdram] Compared to DDR SDRAM which is byte-accessible, GDDR SDRAM is block-accessible.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] The finalized specification was published by JEDEC in July 2017.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] GDDR6 offers increased per-pin bandwidth (up to 16 Gbit/s) and lower operating voltages (1.35 V), increasing performance and decreasing power consumption relative to GDDR5X.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] At Hot Chips 2016, Samsung announced GDDR6 as the successor of GDDR5X.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] Samsung later announced that the first products would be 16 Gbit/s, 1.35 V chips.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] In January 2018, Samsung began mass production of 16 Gb (2 GB) GDDR6 chips, fabricated on a 10 nm class process and with a data rate of up to 18 Gbit/s per pin.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] In February 2017, Micron Technology announced it would release its own GDDR6 products by early 2018.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] Micron began mass production of 8 Gb chips in June 2018.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] SK Hynix announced its GDDR6 products would be released in early 2018.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] SK Hynix announced in April 2017 that its GDDR6 chips would be produced on a 21 nm process and be 10% lower voltage than GDDR5.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] The SK Hynix chips were expected to have a transfer rate of 14–16 Gbit/s.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] The first graphics cards to use SK Hynix's GDDR6 RAM were expected to use 12 GB of RAM with a 384-bit memory bus, yielding a bandwidth of 768 GB/s.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] SK Hynix began mass production in February 2018, with 8 Gbit chips and a data rate of 14 Gbit/s per pin.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] Nvidia officially announced the first consumer graphics cards using GDDR6, the Turing-based GeForce RTX 2080 Ti, RTX 2080 & RTX 2070 on August 20, 2018, RTX 2060 on January 6, 2019 and GTX 1660 Ti on February 22, 2019.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] GDDR6 memory from Samsung Electronics is also used for the Turing-based Quadro RTX series.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] The RTX 20 series initially launched with Micron memory chips, before switching to Samsung chips by November 2018.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] AMD officially announced the Radeon RX 5700, 5700 XT, and 5700 XT 50th Anniversary Edition on June 10, 2019.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] These Navi 10 GPUs utilize 8 GB of GDDR6 memory.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] Micron developed GDDR6X in close collaboration with Nvidia.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] GDDR6X SGRAM had not been standardized by JEDEC yet.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] Nvidia is Micron's only GDDR6X launch partner.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] GDDR6X offers increased per-pin bandwidth between 19–21 Gbit/s with PAM4 signaling, allowing two bits per symbol to be transmitted and replacing earlier NRZ (non return to zero, PAM2) coding that provided only one bit per symbol, thereby limiting the per-pin bandwidth of GDDR6 to 16 Gbit/s.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] The first graphics cards to use GDDR6X are the Nvidia GeForce RTX 3080 and 3090 graphics cards.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] PAM4 signalling is not new but it costs more to implement, partly because it requires more space in chips and is more prone to signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) issues, which mostly limited its use to high speed networking (like 200G Ethernet).
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] GDDR6X consumes 15% less power per transferred bit than GDDR6, but overall power consumption is higher since GDDR6X is faster than GDDR6.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] On average, PAM4 consumes less power and uses fewer pins than differential signalling while still being faster than NRZ.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] GDDR6X is thought to be cheaper than High Bandwidth Memory.
[src:hbm-memory/gddr6-sdram] Samsung announced the development of GDDR6W on November 29, 2022.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] HBM was adopted by JEDEC as an industry standard in October 2013.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The second generation, **HBM2**, was accepted by JEDEC in January 2016.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] JEDEC officially announced the **HBM3** standard on January 27, 2022, and the **HBM4** standard in April 2025.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In 2025, the world's largest manufacturers of HBM include SK Hynix, Samsung Electronics, and Micron Technology.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] TSMC produces the base die for HBM and is planned to be the foundry for several HBM companies in 2026.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] HBM has had an unprecedented demand increase; and in general DRAM (DDR4, DDR, and flash memory/NAND) price has in early 2026 "experienced compounded increases, some exceeding 200%, since early 2025 .. [because of] unprecedented demand coming from the AI sector ..
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] HBM is crowding out commodity DRAM capacity.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] HBM achieves higher bandwidth than DDR4 or GDDR5 while using less power, and in a substantially smaller form factor.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] This is achieved by stacking up to 32 DRAM dies and an optional base die which can include buffer circuitry and test logic.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The stack is often connected to the memory controller on a GPU or CPU through a substrate, such as a silicon interposer.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Alternatively, the memory die could be stacked directly on the CPU or GPU chip.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Within the stack the dies are vertically interconnected by through-silicon vias (TSVs) and microbumps.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The HBM technology is similar in principle to, but incompatible with, the Hybrid Memory Cube (HMC) interface developed by Micron Technology.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The HBM memory bus is very wide in comparison to other DRAM memories such as DDR4 or GDDR5.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] A HBM1 stack of four DRAM dies (4‑Hi) has two 128‑bit channels per die for a total of 8 channels and a width of 1024 bits in total.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] A graphics card/GPU with four 4‑Hi HBM stacks would therefore have a memory bus with a width of 4096 bits.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In comparison, the bus width of GDDR memories is 32 bits, with 16 channels for a graphics card with a 512‑bit memory interface.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The larger number of connections to the memory, relative to DDR4 or GDDR5, required a new method of connecting the HBM memory to the GPU (or other processor).
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] AMD and Nvidia have both used purpose-built silicon chips, called *interposers*, to connect the memory and GPU.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] This interposer has the added advantage of requiring the memory and processor to be physically close, decreasing memory paths.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] However, as semiconductor device fabrication is significantly more expensive than printed circuit board manufacture, this adds cost to the final product.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The HBM DRAM is tightly coupled to the host compute die with a distributed interface.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The interface is divided into independent channels.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The channels are completely independent of one another and are not necessarily synchronous to each other.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] HBM DRAM uses a wide-interface architecture to achieve high-speed, low-power operation.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] HBM1 DRAM used a 500 MHz differential clock CK_t / CK_c (where the suffix "_t" denotes the "true", or "positive", component of the differential pair, and "_c" stands for the "complementary" one).
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Commands are registered at the rising edges of CK_t and CK_c.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Each channel interface maintained a 128‑bit data bus operating at this double data rate (DDR).
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] HBM1 supported transfer rates of 1 GT/s per pin (transferring 1 bit), yielding an overall package bandwidth of 128 GB/s.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The second generation of High Bandwidth Memory, HBM2, also specified up to eight dies per stack and doubled pin transfer rates up to 2 GT/s.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Retaining 1024‑bit wide access, HBM2 was able to reach 256 GB/s memory bandwidth per package.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The HBM2 spec allowed up to 8 GB per package.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] HBM2 was predicted to be especially useful for performance-sensitive consumer applications such as virtual reality.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] On January 19, 2016, Samsung announced early mass production of HBM2, at up to 8 GB per stack.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] SK Hynix also announced availability of 4 GB stacks in August 2016.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In late 2018, JEDEC announced an update to the HBM2 specification, providing for increased bandwidth and capacities.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Up to 307 GB/s per stack (2.5 Tbit/s effective data rate) was then supported in the official specification, though products operating at this speed had already been available.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Additionally, the update added support for 12‑Hi stacks (12 dies) making capacities of up to 24 GB per stack possible.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] On March 20, 2019, Samsung announced their Flashbolt HBM2E, featuring eight dies per stack, a transfer rate of 3.2 GT/s, providing a total of 16 GB and 410 GB/s per stack.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] August 12, 2019, SK Hynix announced their HBM2E, featuring eight dies per stack, a transfer rate of 3.6 GT/s, providing a total of 16 GB and 460 GB/s per stack.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] On July 2, 2020, SK Hynix announced that mass production has begun.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In October 2019, Samsung announced their 12-layered HBM2E.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In late 2020, Micron unveiled that the HBM2E standard would be updated and alongside that they unveiled the then next standard known as HBMnext (later renamed to HBM3).
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] This was to be a big generational leap from HBM2 and the replacement to HBM2E.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] This new VRAM would have come to the market in the Q4 of 2022.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] This would likely have introduce a new architecture as the naming suggests.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] While the architecture might have been overhauled, leaks pointed to performance similar to the updated HBM2E standard.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] This RAM was likely to be used mostly in data center GPUs.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In mid 2021, SK Hynix unveiled some specifications of the HBM3 standard, with 5.2 Gbit/s I/O speeds and bandwidth of 665 GB/s per package, as well as up to 16-high 2.5D and 3D solutions.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] On 20 October 2021, before the JEDEC standard for HBM3 was finalised, SK Hynix was the first memory vendor to announce that it had finished development of HBM3 memory devices.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] According to SK Hynix, the memory would have run as fast as 6.4 Gbit/s/pin, double the data rate of JEDEC-standard HBM2E, which formally topped out at 3.2 Gbit/s/pin, or 78% faster than SK Hynix's own 3.6 Gbit/s/pin HBM2E.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The devices supported a data transfer rate of 6.4 Gbit/s and therefore a single HBM3 stack might have provided a bandwidth of up to 819 GB/s.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The basic bus widths for HBM3 remained unchanged, with a single stack of memory being 1024-bits wide.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] SK Hynix would offer this memory in two capacities: 16 GB and 24 GB, aligning with 8-Hi and 12-Hi stacks respectively.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The stacks consisted of 8 or 12 16 Gb DRAMs that are each 30 μm thick and interconnected using Through Silicon Vias (TSVs).
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] According to Anton Shilov of *Tom's Hardware*, high-performance compute GPUs or FPGAs typically used four or six HBM stacks, so with SK Hynix's HBM3 24 GB stacks they would accordingly get 3.2 TB/s or 4.9 TB/s of memory bandwidth.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] He also noted that SK Hynix's HBM3 chips were square, not rectangular like HBM2 and HBM2E chips.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] According to Chris Mellor of *The Register*, with JEDEC not yet having developed its HBM3 standard, might have meant that SK Hynix would have needed to retrofit its design to a future and faster one.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] JEDEC officially announced the HBM3 standard on January 27, 2022.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The number of memory channels was doubled from 8 channels of 128 bits with HBM2e to 16 channels of 64 bits with HBM3.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Therefore, the total number of data pins of the interface was still 1024.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In June 2022, SK Hynix announced they started mass production of industry's first HBM3 memory to be used with Nvidia's H100 GPU expected to ship in Q3 2022.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The memory would provide H100 with "up to 819 GB/s" of memory bandwidth.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In August 2022, Nvidia announced that its "Hopper" H100 GPU would ship with five active HBM3 sites (out of six on board) offering 80 GB of RAM and 3 TB/s of memory bandwidth (16 GB and 600 GB/s per site).
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] On 30 May 2023, SK Hynix unveiled its HBM3E memory with 8 Gbit/s/pin data processing speed (25% faster than HBM3), which was to enter production in the first half of 2024.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] At 8 GT/s with 1024-bit bus, its bandwidth per stack is increased from 819.2 GB/s as in HBM3 to 1 TB/s.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] On 26 July 2023, Micron announced its HBM3E memory with 9.6 Gbit/s/pin data processing speed (50% faster than HBM3).
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Micron HBM3E memory was a high-performance HBM that used 1β DRAM process technology and advanced packaging to achieve the highest performance, capacity and power efficiency in the industry.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] It could store 24 GB per 8-high cube and allowed data transfer at 1.2 TB/s.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] There would be a 12-high cube with 36 GB capacity in 2024.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In August 2023, Nvidia announced a new version of their GH200 Grace Hopper superchip that utilized 141 GB (144 GiB physical) of HBM3e over a 6144-bit bus providing 50% higher memory bandwidth and 75% higher memory capacity over the HBM3 version.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In May 2023, Samsung announced HBM3P with up to 7.2 Gbit/s which would be in production in 2024.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] On October 20, 2023, Samsung announced their HBM3E "Shinebolt" with up to 9.8 Gbit/s memory.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] On February 26, 2024, Micron announced the mass production of Micron's HBM3E memory.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] On March 19, 2024, SK Hynix announced the mass production of SK Hynix's HBM3E memory.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In September 2024, SK Hynix announced the mass production of its 12-layered HBM3E memory and in November the 16-layered version.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In February 2021, Samsung announced the development of HBM with processing-in-memory (PIM).
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] This new memory brings AI computing capabilities inside the memory, to increase the large-scale processing of data.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] A DRAM-optimised AI engine is placed inside each memory bank to enable parallel processing and minimise data movement.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Samsung claims this will deliver twice the system performance and reduce energy consumption by more than 70%, while not requiring any hardware or software changes to the rest of the system.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In July 2024, JEDEC announced its preliminary specifications for HBM4.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] It lowered the data rate per pin to 6.4 Gbit/s/pin (the level of HBM3) but since it now uses a 2048-bit interface per stack (doubling that of the previous generations), it still achieves greater (1.6TB/s) data rate per stack than HBM3E.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] It will also allow 4GB layers (yielding 64GB in 16-layer configurations).
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In April 2025, JEDEC released the official HBM4 specification.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] It supports transfer speeds of up to 8 Gb/s across a 2048-bit interface, with total bandwidth of up to 2 TB/s, and stack height of 4 to 16, with DRAM die densities of 24Gb or 32Gb, allowing for capacities up to 64GB.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] HBM4 is backwards compatible with HBM3 controllers.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Samsung, Micron, and SK hynix contributed to the standard.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Die-stacked memory was initially commercialized in the flash memory industry.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Toshiba introduced a NAND flash memory chip with eight stacked dies in April 2007, followed by Hynix Semiconductor introducing a NAND flash chip with 24 stacked dies in September 2007.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] 3D-stacked random-access memory (RAM) using through-silicon via (TSV) technology was commercialized by Elpida Memory, which developed the first 8 GB DRAM chip (stacked with four DDR3 SDRAM dies) in September 2009, and released it in June 2011.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In 2011, SK Hynix introduced 16 GB DDR3 memory (40 nm class) using TSV technology, Samsung Electronics introduced 3D-stacked 32 GB DDR3 (30 nm class) based on TSV in September, and then Samsung and Micron Technology announced TSV-based Hybrid Memory Cube (HMC) technology in October.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] JEDEC first released the JESD229 standard for Wide IO memory, the predecessor of HBM featuring four 128 bit channels with single data rate clocking, in December 2011 after several years of work.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The first HBM standard JESD235 followed in October 2013.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The development of High Bandwidth Memory began at AMD in 2008 to solve the problem of ever-increasing power usage and form factor of computer memory.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Over the next several years, AMD developed procedures to solve die-stacking problems with a team led by Senior AMD Fellow Bryan Black.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The development of HBM was completed in 2013, when SK Hynix built the first HBM memory chip.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] HBM was adopted as industry standard JESD235 by JEDEC in October 2013, following a proposal by AMD and SK Hynix in 2010.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] High volume manufacturing began at a Hynix facility in Icheon, South Korea, in 2015.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The first GPU utilizing HBM was the AMD Fiji which was released in June 2015 powering the AMD Radeon R9 Fury X.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In January 2016, Samsung Electronics began early mass production of HBM2.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The same month, HBM2 was accepted by JEDEC as standard JESD235a.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] The first GPU chip utilizing HBM2 is the Nvidia Tesla P100 which was officially announced in April 2016.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] In June 2016, Intel released a family of Xeon Phi processors with 8 stacks of HCDRAM, Micron's version of HBM.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] At Hot Chips in August 2016, both Samsung and Hynix announced a new generation HBM memory technologies.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Both companies announced high performance products expected to have increased density, increased bandwidth, and lower power consumption.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Samsung also announced a lower-cost version of HBM under development targeting mass markets.
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Removing the buffer die and decreasing the number of TSVs lowers cost, though at the expense of a decreased overall bandwidth (200 GB/s).
[src:hbm-memory/hbm3] Nvidia's P100 and H100 GPU were the first products to utilize HBM2 and HBM3 memory, respectively; AMD's MI430X is the first to utilize HBM4.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] Stacks in computing architectures are regions of memory where data is added or removed in a last-in-first-out (LIFO) manner.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] In most modern computer systems, each thread has a reserved region of memory referred to as its stack.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] When a function executes, it may add some of its local state data to the top of the stack; when the function exits it is responsible for removing that data from the stack.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] At a minimum, a thread's stack is used to store the location of a return address provided by the caller in order to allow return statements to return to the correct location.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] The stack is often used to store variables of fixed length local to the currently active functions.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] Programmers may further choose to explicitly use the stack to store local data of variable length.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] If a region of memory lies on the thread's stack, that memory is said to have been allocated on the stack, i.e. stack-based memory allocation (SBMA).
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] This is contrasted with a heap-based memory allocation (HBMA).
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] The SBMA is often closely coupled with a function call stack.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] Because the data is added and removed in a last-in-first-out manner, stack-based memory allocation is very simple and typically much faster than heap-based memory allocation (also known as dynamic memory allocation) e.g.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] Another feature is that memory on the stack is automatically, and very efficiently, reclaimed when the function exits, which can be convenient for the programmer if the data is no longer required.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] (The same applies to longjmp if it moved to a point before the call to `alloca` happened.) If, however, the data needs to be kept in some form, then it must be copied from the stack to the heap before the function exits.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] Therefore, stack based allocation is suitable for temporary data or data which is no longer required after the current function exits.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] A thread's assigned stack size can be as small as only a few bytes on some small CPUs.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] Allocating more memory on the stack than is available can result in a crash due to stack overflow.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] This is also why functions that use `alloca` are usually prevented from being inlined: should such a function be inlined into a loop, the caller would suffer from an unanticipated growth in stack usage, making an overflow much more likely.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] Stack-based allocation can also cause minor performance problems: it leads to variable-size stack frames, so that both stack and frame pointers need to be managed (with fixed-size stack frames, the stack pointer is redundant due to multiplying the stack frame pointer by the size of each frame).
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] This is usually much less costly than calling `malloc` and `free` anyway.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] This conflict is typically resolved by creating a separate chain of heap storage for each call to `alloca`.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] The chain records the stack depth at which each allocation occurs, subsequent calls to `alloca` in any function trim this chain down to the current stack depth to eventually (but not immediately) free any storage on this chain.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] A call to `alloca` with an argument of zero can also be used to trigger the freeing of memory without allocating any more such memory.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] As a consequence of this conflict between `alloca` and local variable storage, using `alloca` might be no more efficient than using `malloc`.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] Many Unix-like systems as well as Microsoft Windows implement a function called `alloca` for dynamically allocating stack memory in a way similar to the heap-based `malloc`.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] A compiler typically translates it to inlined instructions manipulating the stack pointer, similar to how variable-length arrays are handled.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] Although there is no need to explicitly free the memory, there is a risk of undefined behavior due to stack overflow.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] The function was present on Unix systems as early as 32/V (1978), but is not part of Standard C or any POSIX standard.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] A safer version of `alloca` called `_malloca`, which allocates on the heap if the allocation size is too large, and reports stack overflow errors, exists on Microsoft Windows.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] It requires the use of `_freea`. gnulib provides an equivalent interface, albeit instead of throwing an SEH exception on overflow, it delegates to `malloc` when an overlarge size is detected.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] A similar feature can be emulated using manual accounting and size-checking, such as in the uses of `alloca_account` in glibc.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] Some processor families, such as the x86, have special instructions for manipulating the stack of the currently executing thread.
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] Other processor families, including RISC-V, PowerPC and MIPS, do not have explicit stack support, but instead rely on convention and delegate stack management to the operating system's application binary interface (ABI).
[src:hbm-memory/memory-stack] In addition, since the C version C99 (optional since C11), it is possible to create an array on the stack within a function, automatically, known as an *auto VLA* (variable-length array).
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] In electronic engineering, a **through-silicon via** (**TSV**) or **through-chip via** is a vertical electrical connection (via) that passes completely through a silicon wafer or die.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] TSVs are high-performance interconnect techniques used as an alternative to wire-bond and flip chips to create 3D packages and 3D integrated circuits.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] Compared to alternatives such as package-on-package, the interconnect and device density is substantially higher, and the length of the connections becomes shorter.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] Via-middle TSVs are currently a popular option for advanced 3D ICs as well as for interposer stacks.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] TSVs through the front end of line (FEOL) have to be carefully accounted for during the EDA and manufacturing phases.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] That is because TSVs induce thermo-mechanical stress in the FEOL layer, thereby impacting the transistor behaviour.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] CMOS image sensors (CIS) were among the first applications to adopt TSV(s) in volume manufacturing.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] In initial CIS applications, TSVs were formed on the backside of the image sensor wafer to form interconnects, eliminate wire bonds, and allow for reduced form factor and higher-density interconnects.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] Die stacking came about only with the advent of backside illuminated (BSI) CIS, and involved reversing the order of the lens, circuitry, and photodiode from traditional front-side illumination so that the light coming through the lens first hits the photodiode and then the circuitry.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] This was accomplished by flipping the photodiode wafer, thinning the backside, and then bonding it on top of the readout layer using a direct oxide bond, with TSVs as interconnects around the perimeter.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] A 3D package (System in Package, Chip Stack MCM, etc.) contains two or more dies stacked vertically so that they occupy less space and/or have greater connectivity.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] An alternate type of 3D package can be found in IBM's Silicon Carrier Packaging Technology, where ICs are not stacked but a carrier substrate containing TSVs is used to connect multiple ICs together in a package.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] In most 3D packages, the stacked chips are wired together along their edges; this edge wiring slightly increases the length and width of the package and usually requires an extra "interposer" layer between the dies.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] In some new 3D packages, TSVs replace edge wiring by creating vertical connections through the body of the dies.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] The resulting package has no added length or width.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] Because no interposer is required, a TSV 3D package can also be flatter than an edge-wired 3D package.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] This TSV technique is sometimes also referred to as TSS (Through-Silicon Stacking or Thru-Silicon Stacking).
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] A 3D integrated circuit (3D IC) is a single integrated circuit built by stacking silicon wafers and/or dies and interconnecting them vertically so that they behave as a single device.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] By using TSV technology, 3D ICs can pack a great deal of functionality into a small "footprint".
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] The different devices in the stack may be heterogeneous, e.g. combining CMOS logic, DRAM and III-V materials into a single IC.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] In addition, critical electrical paths through the device can be drastically shortened, leading to faster operation.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] The Wide I/O 3D DRAM memory standard (JEDEC JESD229) includes TSVs in the design.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] TSV was not originally designed for 3D integration, but the first 3D chips based on TSV were invented later in the 1980s.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] The first three-dimensional integrated circuit (3D IC) stacked dies fabricated with a TSV process were invented in 1980s Japan.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] Hitachi filed a Japanese patent in 1983, followed by Fujitsu in 1984.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] In 1986, Fujitsu filed a Japanese patent describing a stacked chip structure using TSV.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] In 1989, Mitsumasa Koyonagi of Tohoku University pioneered the technique of wafer-to-wafer bonding with TSV, which he used to fabricate a 3D LSI chip in 1989.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] In 1999, the Association of Super-Advanced Electronics Technologies (ASET) in Japan began funding the development of 3D IC chips using TSV technology, called the "R&D on High Density Electronic System Integration Technology" project.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] The Koyanagi Group at Tohoku University used TSV technology to fabricate a three-layer stacked image sensor chip in 1999, a three-layer memory module in 2000, a three-layer artificial retina chip in 2001, a three-layer microprocessor in 2002, and a ten-layer memory chip in 2005.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] The inter-chip via (ICV) method was developed in 1997 by a Fraunhofer–Siemens research team including Peter Ramm, D.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] Cao-Minh, Manfred Engelhardt and Armin Klumpp.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] It was a variation of the TSV process, and was later called SLID (solid liquid inter-diffusion) technology.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] The term "through-silicon via" (TSV) was coined by Tru-Si Technologies researchers Sergey Savastiouk, O.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] Korczynski, who proposed a TSV method for a 3D wafer-level packaging (WLP) solution in 2000.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] CMOS image sensors utilising TSV were commercialized by companies including Toshiba, Aptina and STMicroelectronics during 2007–2008, with Toshiba naming their technology "Through Chip Via" (TCV).
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] 3D-stacked random-access memory (RAM) was commercialized by Elpida Memory, which developed the first 8 GB DRAM module (stacked with four DDR3 SDRAM dies) in September 2009, and released it in June 2011.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] TSMC announced plans for 3D IC production with TSV technology in January 2010.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] In 2011, SK Hynix introduced 16 GB DDR3 SDRAM (40 nm class) using TSV technology, Samsung introduced 3D-stacked 32 GB DDR3 (30 nm class) based on TSV in September, and then Samsung and Micron Technology announced TSV-based Hybrid Memory Cube (HMC) technology in October.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] In 2013, SK Hynix manufactured the first High Bandwidth Memory (HBM) module based on TSV technology.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] The via middle technology was developed by IMEC under the vision of Eric Beyne.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] The via middle provided the best trade off in terms of cost and interconnect density.
[src:hbm-memory/through-silicon-via] The work was supported by Qualcomm, and then later Nvidia, Xilinx and Altera, who were looking for ways to beat Intel at its game - increasing on-die memory, but then by stacking, rather than scaling.
